    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary with these fields: total_rows, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, unique_cmdb_id_count, top_20_cmdb_id_with_counts, and unique_name_field_with_counts (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name; for error_logs return top_10 distinct messages with counts). Limit lists to the top counts specified. Present results as a concise table-like text for each file. Do not print full raw rows; only the aggregates requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have loaded and summarized the four telemetry files. metric.csv contains 19,671 rows spanning the incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00 UTC+8) across 25 components and many KPIs; trace.csv and log.csv also cover the same time window. error_logs.csv is empty. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is preprocessing: compute global thresholds for each component-KPI (using the full available series) and then extract the data within the incident window for further anomaly detection. To proceed we must compute a global statistic (P95) per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the entire metric.csv, and also report how many points for each component-KPI fall inside the incident window so we can focus metric analysis on the most relevant series.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute these fields for each group using the full available series: total_points (count), global_p95 (95th percentile of value), min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Then filter metric rows to the incident time window: March 23, 2021 18:30 to 19:00 (UTC+8) and compute incident_points (count), incident_min_timestamp, incident_max_timestamp for each group. Return a compact table limited to the top 20 groups sorted by incident_points descending with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points, global_p95, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, incident_points, incident_min_timestamp, incident_max_timestamp. Also return the overall total number of metric rows in the incident window. Do not print full raw time series; only the aggregated table requested. Limit rows to top 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full metric series and extracted incident-window counts. The incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00 UTC+8) contains rows for many component-KPI groups, with the top groups each having 31 incident points (full per-minute coverage). From this we have global thresholds for each group and know which groups are present in the incident window. The next step is to perform anomaly detection: find which component-KPI groups have incident-window points that breach their precomputed global P95 thresholds and quantify severity and timing. This will help narrow candidate faulty components and the earliest anomaly times to locate faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group that has at least one data point inside the incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00, UTC+8), do the following:\n1) Compute global_p95 for the group using the group's full available series (all timestamps in metric.csv).\n2) From the group's incident-window points, count anomaly_count = number of points with value > global_p95.\n3) If anomaly_count>0, compute earliest_anomaly_timestamp (the smallest timestamp among those anomaly points) and max_anomaly_value (maximum value among those anomaly points). Compute severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95.\nReturn a compact table limited to the top 20 groups sorted by severity_ratio descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points (full series count), global_p95, incident_points (count in the incident window), anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio. Also return the overall number of groups that have anomaly_count>0. Do not return raw time series; only the aggregated table requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed anomaly counts per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) inside the incident window using global P95 thresholds from the full series. Results show 463 metric groups with at least one anomaly. Top anomalies by severity include: MG02 TCP CLOSE-WAIT (anomaly at 18:35), MG01 TCP FIN-WAIT (18:40), Mysql02 Innodb row lock waits (18:52), and multiple Tomcat hosts showing elevated CPU WIO (Tomcat04 at 18:30, Tomcat02/03/01 later) and several disk I/O spikes (notably Tomcat01 with multiple disk KPIs at 19:00). Many groups have global_p95==0 producing infinite severity ratios (likely sparse events). Several candidate components (Tomcat01–04, MG01/02, Mysql02, Tomcat04 particularly) show anomalies at different times across the window. To localize the single root cause we must convert these isolated anomaly points into 'faults' (consecutive anomaly sub-series), filter out isolated spikes, and find the earliest significant fault(s) with substantial severity that could explain a single-system failure. The next step is to identify fault segments for anomalous groups and extract their first fault start times and severity to narrow down candidate root-cause components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed per-group global_p95, for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that had anomaly_count>0 in the incident window, detect 'fault' segments defined as consecutive incident-window timestamps where value > global_p95. For each group produce these aggregated fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points (full series count), global_p95, incident_points, number_of_faults (count of consecutive anomaly segments), longest_fault_length_minutes (max consecutive points in any fault), first_fault_start_timestamp (earliest timestamp of the first fault), first_fault_end_timestamp, max_value_within_first_fault, severity_ratio_first_fault = max_value_within_first_fault / global_p95 (use inf if global_p95==0). Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio_first_fault descending. Also return the set of unique cmdb_id values present in that top-20 table. Do not return raw time series; only the aggregated table requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-based preprocessing, anomaly detection, and fault-segment identification. Key findings so far: many component-KPI groups show single-minute faults (number_of_faults=1 and longest_fault_length_minutes=1). Top candidate components from metric faults are: MG01, MG02, Mysql02, Redis02, Tomcat01–Tomcat04. Notable earliest anomaly timestamps among top metric faults are: Tomcat03/Tomcat04 at 18:30, MG02 at 18:35, MG01 at 18:40, Mysql02 at 18:52, and Tomcat01 disk spikes later around 18:50–19:00. However, many high-severity signals are single-point spikes or metrics with global_p95==0 (leading to infinite severity ratios) and could be noisy. According to the root-cause localization rules, we must now use trace data to disambiguate among multiple service-level candidates (pick the most downstream faulty service in trace call chains) and to validate which candidate's fault plausibly propagated as a single-system failure. Therefore we should analyse trace.csv: compute per (cmdb_id, trace_name) global thresholds (P95) over the full series, then find trace anomalies inside the incident window and identify earliest anomalous trace groups and their times and severity. This will help find the most downstream faulty service and the earliest occurrence that could be the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute these over the group's full available series: total_points (count) and global_p95 (95th percentile of value). Then filter trace rows to the incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00, UTC+8) and for each group compute incident_points (count) and anomaly_count = number of incident-window points with value > global_p95. For groups with anomaly_count>0, compute earliest_anomaly_timestamp (smallest timestamp among anomaly points), max_anomaly_value, and severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95 (use inf if global_p95 == 0). Return a compact table limited to the top 20 groups with anomaly_count>0 sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending (earliest first) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points, global_p95, incident_points, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio. Also return the overall count of trace groups with anomaly_count>0 and the set of unique cmdb_id values present in the returned table. Do not return raw time series; only the aggregated table requested. Keep output bounded to top 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found many small but consistent trace anomalies starting at ~18:33–18:34 (UTC+8) across MG01/MG02, IG02, Tomcat02/03 and several docker containers. Metric analysis previously highlighted both network-related sparse spikes (TCP CLOSE-WAIT / FIN-WAIT on MG01/MG02) and I/O/CPU spikes on Tomcat hosts (Tomcat01–04) at varying times (Tomcat03/04 earliest at 18:30; MG02 at 18:35; MG01 at 18:40; Mysql02 at 18:52; Tomcat01 disk spikes ~18:50–19:00). Traces point to an event cluster beginning ~18:33 that involves MG01/MG02 and services downstream (IG02 -> Tomcat02/03). Many trace deviations are modest (≈1.03–1.16× P95), suggesting a transient increase in latency or traffic rather than extreme outliers. Given multiple metric faults across components, we must use logs to (1) confirm which component first showed operational errors or warnings during the incident window, and (2) determine whether those logs indicate a resource reason (e.g., disk errors, OOM, connection timeouts) that can explain propagation. error_logs.csv appears empty so standard logs (log.csv) are primary. Next we should correlate log anomalies (error_count, row_count, etc.) with the metric/trace candidate components and extract earliest log anomaly timestamps and severity to help pick the most likely single root cause component and the exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv and error_logs.csv, do the following:\n1) For log.csv: aggregate by (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full available series to compute total_points and global_p95 (95th percentile) for the group's value. Then filter to the incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00 UTC+8) and compute incident_points, anomaly_count (incident-window points with value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum timestamp among those anomalies), max_anomaly_value, and severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95 (use inf when global_p95==0). Return a compact table limited to top 20 groups with anomaly_count>0 sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and include these columns: cmdb_id, log_name, total_points, global_p95, incident_points, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio. Also return the total number of log groups with anomaly_count>0 and the set of unique cmdb_id values present in the returned table.\n2) For error_logs.csv: report whether the file contains any rows; if non-empty, return the top 10 distinct messages with counts and the earliest timestamp for each message. If empty, state explicitly that error_logs.csv contains zero rows.\nKeep outputs compact and bounded (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, anomaly detection, fault segmentation, and cross-modal correlation. Key outcomes so far: metric analysis found many single-minute faults across MG01, MG02, Tomcat01–04, Mysql02, Redis02. Trace anomalies cluster earliest at ~18:33–18:34 involving MG02/MG01, IG02 and Tomcat02/03. Log anomalies are modest and mostly appear slightly later (Tomcat logs from ~18:34–18:50; no entries in error_logs.csv). A cross-modal correlation across candidate components {'MG01','MG02','Tomcat01','Tomcat02','Tomcat03','Tomcat04','Mysql02','Redis02'} indicates MG01 has the earliest combined non-null timestamp (earliest_metric_fault = 2021-03-23 18:30:00 UTC+8) and an infinite metric severity_ratio (global_p95 == 0 with a positive spike), making it the top lead. However, many top metric faults are single-minute spikes (potential noise), and MG01 lacks corroborating log anomalies in log.csv. According to the diagnosis rules, before declaring MG01 as the root cause we must confirm MG01's faults are real (not isolated noisy spikes), identify the faulty resource (network/CPU/memory/disk/JVM), and verify propagation via traces. Therefore we need to inspect MG01 metric anomalies in detail: which KPIs showed anomalies in the incident window, their earliest anomaly timestamps, max values and global P95, incident coverage, and severity ratios. This will tell us whether MG01 experienced a substantive multi-point fault or only isolated spikes, and which resource reason (e.g., network TCP CLOSE-WAIT/FIN-WAIT) is implicated.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on MG01. Using metric.csv (compute global P95 per MG01 kpi_name using the full series), identify all MG01 kpi_name groups that have anomaly points in the incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00 UTC+8). For each such KPI return a compact row with: kpi_name, total_points (full series), global_p95, incident_points (count in window), anomaly_count (points with value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95 (use inf if global_p95==0). Sort results by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and limit to top 50 rows. Also return a single-line summary: whether MG01 has any KPI with a fault sub-series longer than 1 minute (i.e., longest fault length > 1) and, if so, the KPI name and its first_fault_start_timestamp. Keep outputs compact and do not return raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the full workflow: preprocessed metrics/traces/logs, computed global P95 thresholds per group, detected anomalies in the incident window, identified fault segments, and correlated anomalies across modalities for candidate components. Key findings: metric faults appear earliest (many components show first metric anomalies at 18:30 UTC+8), trace anomalies cluster slightly later around 18:33–18:34 involving MG02/MG01, IG02 and Tomcat02/03, and log anomalies are modest and mostly later (18:34–18:50). Cross-modal correlation across candidates {'MG01','MG02','Tomcat01','Tomcat02','Tomcat03','Tomcat04','Mysql02','Redis02'} shows MG01 has the earliest combined non-null timestamp (earliest_metric_fault = 2021-03-23 18:30:00) and some infinite severity ratios for sparse network KPIs, making MG01 a top lead. However, several highest-severity metric events are single-minute spikes (possible noise) and traces show an early cluster centered on MG02 at 18:33. According to the localization rules, we must (1) confirm whether MG01's anomalies constitute a substantive fault (consecutive anomalous minutes and non-marginal severity), (2) use traces to identify the most downstream faulty service in affected call chains, and (3) use logs to corroborate the suspected resource reason. We have partial evidence but not yet a decisive single root cause: more focused trace-call-chain inspection for the earliest anomalous traces (18:33–18:35) is needed to determine whether MG02 or MG01 is the true origin and which downstream service is faulty.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously computed trace-group anomalies, extract all trace groups whose earliest_anomaly_timestamp is between 2021-03-23 18:33:00 and 2021-03-23 18:35:00 (inclusive, UTC+8). For each group return these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, global_p95, severity_ratio, incident_points. Sort rows by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and limit to top 50 rows. Also return the set of unique cmdb_id values present in this filtered table. Keep output compact (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected trace anomalies between 18:33–18:35 and found an earliest spike pair at 18:33 between dockerA2 and MG02, followed by a cluster at 18:34 involving MG01 flows (dockerB1/dockerB2/dockerA1 → MG01) and other services. Earlier metric analysis showed many components with metric spikes at 18:30 (including MG01 and MG02), but many of those metric spikes were single-minute events or had global_p95==0 (sparse events producing infinite severity ratios), which can be noisy. Trace anomalies are more clustered and show the earliest cross-component activity at 18:33 with MG02 involved. To decide the single root cause, we need to confirm whether MG02's metric anomalies are substantive faults (consecutive anomaly minutes and non-marginal severity) or isolated spikes; this will let us choose between MG02 (trace-earliest at 18:33) and MG01 (metric-earliest at 18:30 but trace anomalies later at 18:34). Therefore we should perform the same detailed KPI-level fault-segment check for MG02 that we did for MG01 to see whether MG02 has multi-minute faults or high-severity resource issues that could be the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on MG02. Using metric.csv (compute global P95 per MG02 kpi_name using the full series), identify all MG02 kpi_name groups that have anomaly points in the incident window (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00 UTC+8). For each KPI return: kpi_name, total_points (full series), global_p95, incident_points (count in window), anomaly_count (points with value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95 (use inf if global_p95==0), longest_fault_length (minutes), first_fault_start_timestamp. Sort by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and limit to top 50 rows. Also return a single-line indicator: whether MG02 has any KPI with longest_fault_length > 1 and, if so, the KPI name and its first_fault_start_timestamp. Keep outputs compact and do not return raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected MG02 metric-level anomalies and found multiple KPI spikes with earliest anomalies at 18:30 (UTC+8) but no KPI showing a multi-minute fault (indicator: 'MG02 has no KPI with longest_fault_length > 1'). Trace analysis showed the earliest cross-component trace anomaly at 18:33 (dockerA2 <-> MG02), and a cluster at 18:34 involving MG01 flows. MG01 had the earliest cross-modal timestamp overall (metric at 18:30) and at least one KPI with a fault >1 minute (but that long fault started later at ~18:47), while MG02 shows trace-earliest activity at 18:33 but only single-minute metric spikes. The root cause must be a single failure; to choose between MG02 and MG01 (and to validate MG02 as the origin of the 18:33 trace spike) we need to confirm whether MG02 experienced network-related faults (TCP/NETWORK KPIs) that could explain trace propagation. MG02's KPI table previously returned mostly disk/CPU items; network KPIs may exist deeper in the MG02 set. Therefore we need a focused check of MG02 network-related KPIs for the incident window to see if they show substantive anomalies (consecutive minutes, non-marginal severity) that would support MG02 as the root cause around 18:33–18:35.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For MG02 only: scan metric.csv for MG02 KPIs whose kpi_name contains 'NETWORK' or 'TCP' (case-insensitive). For each matching (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute using the group's full series: total_points and global_p95 (95th percentile). Then filter the group's incident-window points (2021-03-23 18:30 to 19:00 UTC+8) and compute incident_points, anomaly_count (value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, severity_ratio = max_anomaly_value / global_p95 (use inf if global_p95 == 0), longest_fault_length (minutes), and first_fault_start_timestamp. Return a compact table sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending limited to top 20 rows, plus a short summary: number_of_network_kpis_with_anomaly (>0), and whether any such KPI has longest_fault_length > 1 (and if so list that KPI and its first_fault_start_timestamp). Keep output bounded and do not return raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected MG02 network/TCP KPIs for the incident window. Findings: MG02 has several NETWORK/TCP anomalies (7 groups) with earliest relevant activity at 18:34–18:35 (TotalTcpConnNum and NETBandwidthUtil at 18:34; TCP-CLOSE-WAIT at 18:35 with global_p95==0 producing inf severity; TCP-FIN-WAIT spike at 18:44). None of these network KPIs exhibit multi-minute continuous faults (longest_fault_length = 1 for all). Trace analysis showed the earliest cross-component spike at 18:33 between dockerA2 and MG02 (row_count), followed by a broader cluster at 18:34 that involves MG01 flows. MG01 had the earliest metric anomalies at 18:30 (many single-minute spikes) and later some longer faults, but MG02 shows trace-earliest activity at 18:33 despite only single-minute metric network spikes. Conclusion so far: MG02 shows some short network anomalies aligned with the earliest trace activity (18:33–18:35), but lacks sustained multi-minute network faults. MG01 has earlier metric spikes (18:30) but traces implicate MG02 earlier (18:33). To disambiguate which component is the single root cause, we need to determine whether any service in the 18:33–18:35 trace window experienced latency/duration increases (duration-type trace anomalies), since duration spikes are strong indicators of service degradation and can help identify the most downstream faulty service in call chains. The next step is to extract duration-related trace anomalies in that 18:33–18:35 window to see which components show latency increases and their earliest timestamps and severities.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, filter trace groups whose earliest_anomaly_timestamp is between 2021-03-23 18:33:00 and 2021-03-23 18:35:00 (UTC+8) AND whose trace_name contains the substring 'duration' (case-insensitive) or 'duration_p95' or 'duration_mean'. For each matching group compute and return: cmdb_id, trace_name, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_anomaly_value, global_p95, severity_ratio (max_anomaly_value / global_p95, use inf if global_p95==0), and incident_points. Sort by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and limit to top 50 rows. Also return the set of unique cmdb_id values present in this filtered result. Keep output compact and do not return raw time series."
}

Based on the cross-modal analysis (metrics, traces, logs), the most likely single root cause is MG01 experiencing a short but impactful latency spike that first appears in traces at 2021-03-23 18:35:00 (UTC+8).

